Perth, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Schotland","Luss, Loch Lomond, Scotland":"Luss, Argyll and Bute, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1410–1454":"1410–1454","1420–1479":"1420–1479","1388–1443":"1388–1443","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1387–1439":"1387–1439","1390–1438":"1390–1438","1390":"1390","1425":"1425","1479":"1479","1500":"1500","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1454":"1454","1388":"1388","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","24 SEP 1439":"24 September 1439","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland","Luss, Loch Lomond, Scotland":"Luss, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom","Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Cockburnspath, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Colquhoun","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Alastair.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Colquhoun in Dumbartonshire. The name appears to derive from Gaelic <i>còil</i>, <i>cùil</i> ‘nook, corner’, or <i>coill(e)</i> ‘wood’ + <i>cumhann</i> ‘narrow’. The usual Scottish pronunciation is <i>ka-hoon</i>. This is the name of a Scottish family descended from Umfridus de Kilpatrick, who acquired lands in the barony of Colquhoun during the reign of Alexander II (1214–49)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cohoon","meanings":["English (Cheshire) and Scottish: variant of   Colquhoun  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Calhoun","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Colquhoun  .","History: This prominent early American name was brought across the Atlantic Ocean by Scotch-Irish pioneers who entered Pennsylvania <i>c.</i> 1733. The American statesman John <i>c.</i> Calhoun (1782–1850), born in Abbeville District, SC, served in both houses of Congress, was secretary of war, and vice president of the US (1825–32)."]},{"name":"Kahoun","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]},{"name":"Cahoon","meanings":["Irish (Down and Antrim): variant (reflecting the traditional pronunciation) of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]},{"name":"Calhoon","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘Morning dew’; also ‘generosity’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Colquhoun was born in 1410, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Malcolm Colquhoun Baron of Luss, was 23 and her mother, Elizabeth Dunbar, was 20. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir David Dunbar. She died in 1454, in her hometown, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1410–1454":"1410–1454","1420–1479":"1420–1479","1388–1443":"1388–1443","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1387–1439":"1387–1439","1390–1438":"1390–1438","1390":"1390","1425